From c236a6be7ee88ec1f909bad8a4a133c998c6fd31 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Sertonix <sertonix@posteo.net>
Date: Mon, 15 Jun 2026 15:48:43 +0200
Subject: [PATCH] abuild: run config.sub in sh(1) from PATH

The official config.sub uses `#! /bin/sh` as shebang[0]. Fedora linux
seem to modify shebangs of packaged files, including the config.sub that
autoconf will include in the `make dist` output[1][2]. autoconf itself
always invokes config.sub through the shell which avoids this issue and
is technically a bit more portable (since POSIX only specifies that a
POSIX shell is findable through PATH, not the absolute location). Change
abuild to call config.sub in a similar way (but for the sake of
simplicitly not allow overwriting the shell).

This would break if anybody write a custom config.sub that is not a
portable shell script. In that case one should probably not use
update_config_sub.

[0]: https://cgit.git.savannah.gnu.org/cgit/config.git/tree/config.sub
[1]: https://github.com/hunspell/hunspell/issues/1127
[2]: https://bugzilla.redhat.com/show_bug.cgi?id=2486114
---
 abuild.in | 2 +-
 1 file changed, 1 insertion(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/abuild.in b/abuild.in
index 0440002..546d88e 100644
--- a/abuild.in
+++ b/abuild.in
@@ -652,7 +652,7 @@ mkusers() {
 # helper to update config.sub to a recent version
 update_config_sub() {
 	find . -name config.sub | (local changed=false; while read f; do
-		if ! ./$f loongarch64-alpine-linux-musl 2>/dev/null; then
+		if ! sh "$f" loongarch64-alpine-linux-musl 2>/dev/null; then
 			msg "Updating $f"
 			cp "$sharedir"/${f##*/} "$f" || return 1
 			changed=true
-- 
